00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:28.900
so that it can iterate on different versions of the model.

00:28:29.439 --> 00:28:31.739
So I will use the pins package here.

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:35.400
Same S3 bucket that I'm using for my data,

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:37.760
I can use it for my model as well.

00:28:37.900 --> 00:28:39.339
So I'm using the same bucket

00:28:39.459 --> 00:28:42.739
and using the Petaver pin write function

00:28:42.859 --> 00:28:47.199
to pin this model on the same default bucket that is associated.

00:28:47.339 --> 00:28:50.439
But if in your case, you're interacting with some other resource

00:28:50.579 --> 00:28:53.400
like PositConnect, you want to save your pin on PositConnect

00:28:53.540 --> 00:28:56.839
or another S3 bucket, you can change that and save that too.

00:28:57.739 --> 00:29:01.680
Now, this is where I would say the selling point

00:29:01.800 --> 00:29:03.300
of using Petaver in this scenario

00:29:03.439 --> 00:29:07.040
is Petaver has the Petaver deploy SageMaker function

00:29:07.180 --> 00:29:10.339
already available, which does all the hard work

00:29:10.479 --> 00:29:12.939
of what we have done in terms of the deployment so far.

00:29:13.079 --> 00:29:15.800
So you don't need to know the SageMaker package.

00:29:15.939 --> 00:29:18.079
You can directly use this function,

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:20.939
which will do all of the stuff for you.

00:29:21.079 --> 00:29:25.979
So I will provide it to the board where the pinned model is,

00:29:26.119 --> 00:29:27.819
what is the name of that pin?

00:29:27.939 --> 00:29:30.040
Again, the same instance type I want to run it on

00:29:30.180 --> 00:29:32.119
and any other additional arguments.

00:29:32.819 --> 00:29:36.920
And what this Petaver deploy SageMaker function

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:41.439
the way it's doing in the backend is it's doing three things for you,

00:29:41.579 --> 00:29:45.920
which is what we did step by step already to the SageMaker API.

00:29:46.020 --> 00:29:49.359
So it will first build the Docker image needed to run this model.

00:29:50.219 --> 00:29:53.819
And then it will add the change or deploy it as a SageMaker

00:29:53.959 --> 00:29:55.479
or create the SageMaker model.

00:29:55.619 --> 00:29:57.760
And then it also deploy the endpoint for you.

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:01.180
So all these three steps that you can also do separately,

00:30:01.319 --> 00:30:02.780
but this function is doing it for you.

00:30:02.920 --> 00:30:05.680
So there's only I need this line of code.

00:30:05.819 --> 00:30:09.959
And this model that I have locally will be converted to a SageMaker model

00:30:10.079 --> 00:30:12.260
and already deployed on SageMaker.

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:15.119
Again, to save us time, I've already done that deployment.

00:30:15.319 --> 00:30:18.219
And like the other model that we already deployed,

00:30:18.359 --> 00:30:22.119
my model is also deployed and available for you to interact with.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:26.420
So this is a great way to get into working with SageMaker.

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:29.560
If you don't know the SageMaker CLI, but you do know Vector,

00:30:29.680 --> 00:30:31.880
which uses the basic ID model stuff.

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:35.479
And then there are multiple ways to get into SageMaker.

00:30:35.619 --> 00:30:38.719
And then this workflow now can be extended

00:30:38.859 --> 00:30:41.020
to create different other workflows within SageMaker

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:42.760
since I've already done the modeling.

00:30:43.760 --> 00:30:45.959
So this is all what I had and I wanted to show

00:30:46.099 --> 00:30:49.619
and I'm going to pass it on back to Tom to talk more about this.

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:51.319
Thanks for your time.

00:30:51.459 --> 00:30:53.219
So as we kind of wrap up for the day,

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:57.060
I'll go back to this slide around the resources that are available.

00:30:57.199 --> 00:31:00.300
So I can walk through kind of a bunch of different ways

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:03.900
that R can be used in our studio can be used inside SageMaker,

00:31:04.020 --> 00:31:07.119
both natively from using some of the SDKs

00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:09.920
and software tooling that SageMaker provides,

00:31:10.060 --> 00:31:12.219
as well as some of the tooling that we provide here at Posit

00:31:12.319 --> 00:31:14.119
through things like tidy models and vetiver.

